In [[game theory]], a '''Markov strategy''' is one that depends only on [[state variables]] that summarize the history of the game in one way or another.<ref>{{cite book|last=Fudenberg|first=Drew|title=Game Theory|year=1995|publisher=The MIT Press|location=Cambridge, MA|isbn=0-262-06141-4|pages=501–40}}</ref> For instance, a state variable can be the current play in a repeated game, or it can be any interpretation of a recent sequence of play.

A profile of Markov strategies is a Markov perfect equilibrium if it is a Nash equilibrium in every state of the game.

