{{Infobox Wrestling event |name = PMG Clash of Legends |image = |promotion = [[Memphis Wrestling]] |brand = |date = April 27, 2007 |venue = [[FedExForum]] |city = [[Memphis, Tennessee]] |attendance = 2,200 <ref name="Attendance">{{ cite web | url = http://rasslinriotnews.blogspot.com/2007/05/col-coverage-official-gate-released.html | author = Tramel, B.| title = COL Coverage: Official Gate Released!!! | publisher= Rasslin' Riot Online via [[Blogger (service)|Blogger.com]] | accessdate = May 6, 2007 | date = May 5, 2007 }}</ref> |lastevent = |nextevent = }} The '''''PMG Clash of Legends, Starring Hulk Hogan''''' was an [[United States|American]] [[professional wrestling]] [[pay-per-view]] (PPV) event (in various territories) promoted by [[Memphis Wrestling]] owner [[Corey Maclin]] in conjunction with [[Hulk Hogan]], which took place on April 27, 2007 in the [[FedExForum]] in [[Memphis, Tennessee]]. The event attracted a degree of attention after a scheduled match between [[WWE Hall of Fame|Hall of]] [[Wrestling Observer Newsletter Hall of Fame|Famers]] Hogan and [[Jerry Lawler]] was vetoed by [[World Wrestling Entertainment]] (WWE), resulting in a lawsuit between Maclin and WWE. It was described by the [[Dave Meltzer|Wrestling Observer]] as "the biggest [[Independent circuit|indie]] undertaking in the U.S. geared toward the non-[[Hispanic]] market in many years".<ref name="WO3">{{ cite web | url = http://www.wrestlingobserver.com/wo/news/headlines/default.asp?aID=19208 | author = | title = More updates on Lawler vs. Hogan | publisher=[[Dave Meltzer|Wrestling Observer]] | accessdate = April 13, 2007 | date = April 11, 2007 }}</ref>
==History== The ''PMG Clash of Legends'' had originally been scheduled to take place in the [[Mid-South Coliseum]]. However, the Mid-South Coliseum was closed in late 2005 due to failure to comply with [[Disability rights movement|disabled accessibility]] regulations. When the FedExForum was chosen as a replacement, the operators of the FedExForum contacted WWE, which had in the past held events in the FedExForum, to ensure that WWE did not object to an alternative professional wrestling promotion staging an event there. WWE did not object to the event taking place. Following the announcement that Lawler would not be allowed to wrestle at the event, WWE offered to refund Maclin's deposit on the rental of the FedExForum. He declined.<ref name="WO2">{{ cite web|url=http://www.wrestlingobserver.com/wo/news/headlines/default.asp?aID=19218|last=Meltzer|first=Dave|title= Update on Memphis situation regarding WWE and Memphis Wrestling|publisher=Wrestling Observer Newsletter|accessdate=2007-04-13|date= }}</ref>
Initially, the sole match announced for the event was the titular "Clash of Legends", a bout between Hogan and Memphis Wrestling mainstay Lawler that had been promoted on the Memphis Wrestling television show ''Memphis Wrestling Prime Time'' for several months.<ref name="WO">{{ cite web|url=http://www.wrestlingobserver.com/wo/news/headlines/default.asp?aID=19108|last=Tramel|first=B|title=Memphis Wrestling TV report|publisher=Wrestling Observer Newsletter|accessdate=2007-04-13|date=2007-04-01|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070525134150/http://www.wrestlingobserver.com/wo/news/headlines/default.asp?aID=19108|archivedate=May 25, 2007}}</ref><ref name="Torch">{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/artman/publish/article_19889.shtml|last=Keller|first=Wade|title=WWE News: Date for Hulk Hogan's return to the ring announced today, facing Lawler |publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=2007-04-13|date=2007-03-31 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070428100531/http://www.pwtorch.com/artman/publish/article_19889.shtml <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-04-28}}</ref> However, on April 12, 2007, Lawler announced in a [[news conference]] that WWE had barred him from wrestling Hogan on the basis that [[NBC Universal]] employees (which includes Lawler, on the basis of co-hosting the NBC Universal-owned [[USA Network]]'s ''[[WWE Raw]]'', and his appearances on the biannual ''[[WWE Saturday Night's Main Event]]'') are contractually prohibited from appearing on any of the channels owned by [[MTV Networks]], which includes [[VH1]], the channel on which ''[[Hogan Knows Best]]'', a [[reality television]] series starring Hogan, airs.<ref name="MM">{{cite web|url=http://www.mikemooneyham.com/pages/viewfull.cfm?ObjectID=F6EF190B-3048-8903-32706EB4EECC196C|last=Mooneyham|first=Mike|title=Hogan-Lawler Called Off|publisher= mikemooneyham.com|accessdate=2007-05-12|date=2007-04-15| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070822103347/http://www.mikemooneyham.com/pages/viewfull.cfm?ObjectID=F6EF190B-3048-8903-32706EB4EECC196C| archivedate = August 22, 2007}}</ref>
Following the cancellation of the Hogan-Lawler match, Memphis Wrestling owner Corey Maclin announced that Hogan would instead wrestle [[Paul Wight]] in Wight's first match since leaving WWE in December 2006. When referred to by the [[ring name]] he used in WWE, "The Big Show", Wight stated that this was his "[[slave name]]" and that he was to be referred to as "'The Great' Paul Wight".<ref name="MM" />
In response to Maclin's announcement, WWE immediately banned all WWE employees from appearing at Memphis Wrestling events, with the result that [[The Boogeyman (wrestler)|The Boogeyman]], [[Charlie Haas]] and [[Shelton Benjamin]] were all obliged to cancel their scheduled appearances at the April 13, 2007 Memphis Wrestling show in [[Tunica, Mississippi]].<ref name="WO2"/> [[Robert Gibson (wrestler)|Robert Gibson]] was to team with his longtime [[The Rock 'n' Roll Express|Rock 'n' Roll Express]] partner [[Ricky Morton]] to face Too Cool II, however WWE pulled Gibson from the event as well, as he was a WWE [[Road Agent (professional wrestling)|producer]]. Gibson would be replaced by [[Kid Kash]], and [[Bobby Eaton]] filled Kash's original spot as [[Koko B. Ware]]'s tag team partner against [[Bill Dundee]] and [[Dutch Mantel]].<ref name="PWI2842007">{{cite journal|last=Johnson|first=M|title=WWE pulls another talent from Memphis Hulk Hogan event|publisher=Pro Wrestling Insider|date=2007-04-25}}</ref>
The event was hosted by Maclin and [[Lance Russell]], and [[List of mayors of Memphis, Tennessee|mayor of Memphis]] [[W. W. Herenton]] served as [[timekeeper]]. Colin Bowman was brought in at the last minute as the Show Director.<ref name="WO3"/><ref name="WO2" /><ref name="Results">{{ cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/artman/publish/article_20124.shtml|last=Tramel|first=Brian| title=4/27 Memphis Wrestling: Hogan vs. Paul Wight, Beefcake, Bagwell, Abdullah, Valentine, Slick|publisher=[[Wade Keller|Pro Wrestling Torch]]|accessdate=2007-04-28|date=2007-04-28| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070515162924/http://www.pwtorch.com/artman/publish/article_20124.shtml| archivedate = May 15, 2007}}</ref>
On May 5, 2007, it was revealed that 2,200 fans attended the event, yielding a [[United States dollar|$]]104,500 gate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rasslinriotnews.blogspot.com/2007/05/col-coverage-official-gate-released.html|last=Tramel| first=Brian|title=COL Coverage: Official Gate Released!!!|publisher= Rasslin' Riot Online via [[Blogger (service)|Blogger.com]]| accessdate=2007-05-06|date=2007-05-05}}</ref>
In January 2008, Maclin filed a claim for [[punitive damages]] against WWE and WWE Chairman [[Vince McMahon]] in the [[Shelby County, Tennessee|Shelby County]] [[circuit court]], alleging that WWE and McMahon had breached section two of the [[Sherman Antitrust Act]].<ref name="Dries">{{ cite web|url=http://www.memphisdailynews.com/Editorial/StoryLead.aspx?id=100606|last=Dries| first=Bill|title=Memphis Promoter Files Suit Against WWE|publisher=[[The Daily News (Memphis)|The Daily News]]|accessdate= 2008-01-12|date=2008-01-11}}</ref>
